Introduction to Pandas
What is Pandas?
Pandas is a Python library used for reading, cleaning, analyzing and manipulating structured data. It is widely used in Data Science, Machine Learning and AI.
Import
import pandas as pd
NumPy vs Pandas
NumPy works with arrays.
Pandas works with tables (Series and DataFrames).
Series
A Series is a one-dimensional labeled array.
Example:
marks = pd.Series([85,90,88])
DataFrame
A DataFrame is a two-dimensional table.
Example:
df = pd.DataFrame({'Name':['Alice','Bob'],'Age':[20,21],'Marks':[85,90]})
Useful Properties
df.shape -> (rows, columns)
df.columns -> Column names
df.dtypes -> Data types
Viewing Data
df.head()
df.head(2)
df.tail()
df.tail(2)
Dataset Summary
df.info() -> Dataset information
df.describe() -> Statistical summary
Selecting Columns
df['Name'] -> Series
df[['Name','Marks']] -> DataFrame
Adding Columns
df['City']='Chennai'
Common Mistakes
Use quotes around column names.
Single brackets return a Series.
Double brackets return a DataFrame.
Interview Questions
1. What is Pandas?
2. Difference between Series and DataFrame?
3. Difference between df['Age'] and df[['Age']]?
